29
00:01:28,340 --> 00:01:30,680
Angle mode is the easiest for people to learn.

30
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:33,060
I always start people off by teaching them angle mode.

31
00:01:33,340 --> 00:01:35,540
The throttle and the yaw are always the same.

32
00:01:35,660 --> 00:01:40,100
So, our left stick here, our throttle and the yaw are always going to be the same, no matter if it's angle or acro mode.

33
00:01:40,180 --> 00:01:43,780
So, what I'm going to be focusing on right now is our right stick, our pitch, and our roll.

34
00:01:44,260 --> 00:01:49,080
When we pitch the drone forwards in angle mode, it's only limited to a certain height.

35
00:01:49,080 --> 00:01:54,880
And wherever you put the stick, if I have the stick right here, I put it halfway forwards.

36
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:57,800
The drone is going to tilt halfway of its range limit.

37
00:01:58,120 --> 00:02:00,660
And if I push it all the way forwards, it's going to tilt all the way forwards.

38
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:08,940
So, if this drone can only tilt 30 degrees in any given direction, and if I push my stick halfway to the top, the drone is going to tilt 15 degrees.

39
00:02:08,940 --> 00:02:11,400
And if I push it all the way, it's going to tilt 30 degrees.

40
00:02:12,260 --> 00:02:13,480
So, the stick's always in the middle.

41
00:02:13,560 --> 00:02:16,520
So, if I pull it down halfway, the drone would tilt back 15 degrees.

42
00:02:16,860 --> 00:02:19,080
Back all the way, and it would tilt back 30 degrees.

43
00:02:19,280 --> 00:02:22,420
When I release the stick, the drone would just snap back to level.

44
00:02:22,700 --> 00:02:23,940
And that's how angle mode works.

45
00:02:24,020 --> 00:02:29,780
It's always actively trying to level out the drone or put it at the exact angle corresponding to where your stick is at.

46
00:02:30,120 --> 00:02:31,680
Now, acro mode is a little different.

47
00:02:31,680 --> 00:02:43,040
Instead of correlating the position of your stick with the angle of the drone, acro mode correlates the position of your stick with the speed to rotate the drone at, in that direction that your stick is in.

48
00:02:43,520 --> 00:02:51,580
So, if I push my stick all the way forwards, the drone is going to rotate forwards really fast and keep flipping forwards until I release my stick.

49
00:02:52,660 --> 00:02:58,840
If I push my stick halfway forwards, the drone is going to start rotating forwards at half that speed.

50
00:02:58,840 --> 00:03:04,640
And again, it's not locked to a constant angle, so it's just going to be a constant rotation.

51
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:10,940
In acro mode as well, whenever you release that stick, the drone does not snap back to level like it does in angle mode.

52
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:13,900
It will continue on in whatever position you left it in.

53
00:03:14,460 --> 00:03:22,680
So, if I used my roll stick and I rolled my drone sideways, and then I just let go of my stick, my drone would stay like this.

54
00:03:22,720 --> 00:03:26,560
I'd have to actively roll to the left to get my drone back to level.

55
00:03:26,560 --> 00:03:33,960
Now that you understand the basics of angle mode, the drone will always stay within a certain angle limit, and the angle corresponds to how far you're pushing the stick.

56
00:03:34,460 --> 00:03:43,420
And acro mode, where there isn't a max range the drone can go, it can go wherever, and the speed at which it turns is defined by how fast you push the stick.

